@TomAugspurger @mrocklin I have modified the test a bit. It is possible that although both `pandas` and `dask` return the correct results, their order might be different (due to splitting in chunks and concatenating and re-applying). Further, the final result can have a `RangeIndex`, a `MultiIndex` or even an `Int64Index`. Thus, to account for equality of the results, I have converted the outputs to dictionaries and then compared them.

I have also added a total of 24 tests in the latest commit. Hopefully, this should suffice.

Edit: Since the output can be any of `RangeIndex`, a `MultiIndex`, etc. Thus, we cannot know the `metadata` of the index beforehand. (Plus the type of index can vary for each chunk as well). Hence, the test uses `assert` (and not `assert_eq`) and compares the outputs directly by converting them to `dicts`.

@TomAugspurger @mrocklin This PR should be finally ready. I have added 576 tests in total, all of which pass on my local machine. Hopefully, they cover all possible variations of inputs that can be passed. I can add more if needed.

I could now appreciate a review :)

I am just unsure if the tests will pass on `Windows CI / build (3.6)` due to an older / different version of pandas perhaps. The error that comes is `nlargest() got an unexpected keyword argument 'axis'`. I hope it passes though.
